messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /consumer/printrequest/{printRequestID}/submit

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- false

Acceptable methods (based on the code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The controller method finishAndSubmitPrintRequest is annotated with:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/printrequest/{printRequestID}/submit", method = RequestMethod.POST)
  This explicitly maps only the POST method for the path /consumer/printrequest/{printRequestID}/submit (the path parameter name matches the @PathVariable("printRequestID") in the method signature).
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping that would add a prefix, so the full path is exactly the method-level value.
- Because the mapping explicitly specifies RequestMethod.POST, only POST is considered acceptable according to the source code. I did not assume framework-provided implicit support (e.g., automatic HEAD for GET or automatic OPTIONS handling); those are not declared in the code itself, so they are reported as false.
